data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType` which combines the type check and gives a clear failure message:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

Or if you want to avoid the cast entirely and still access properties, use the generic overload (MSTest 3.x+) which returns the typed instance:

```csharp
var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
```

This gives you a meaningful test failure ("Expected type EmailHandler, actual type SmsHandler") instead of an `InvalidCastException` if the factory returns the wrong type.
